data.title: Gabby Giffords and husband Mark Kelly reveal their 'mystical' connection as they pose for intimate photos in Vogue magazine
data.meta_description: Former Congresswoman Gabrielle Giffords posed with her husband Mark Kelly for a Vogue photo shoot in an article for the magazine's March 2013 issue.
data.text:
It's been two years since former Rep. Gabrielle Giffords was injured in a shooting massacre in a Tucson supermarket parking lot.

As a mark of her amazing recovery from a severe brain injury, the former Congresswoman posed with her husband Mark Kelly for a Vogue photo shoot as they discuss their relationship and new gun control activism in an article for the magazine's March 2013 issue.

The former lawmaker is pictured relaxing at her Arizona home as she gazes longingly at her husband - softly taking hold of Kelly's hand as the desert sun streams in to surround them.

Scroll down for video.

Gorgeous Gabby: Former Rep. Gabrielle Giffords, D-Ariz., left, and her husband Mark Kelly discuss their gun regulation effort in the March 2013 issue of Vogue magazine

Kelly, a former NASA astronaut, has constantly been by his wife's side since she was targeted by gunman Jared Lee Loughner on January 8, 2011.

Lougher began shooting into a crowd, who had gathered in the parking lot of a Safeway supermarket where Giffords was holding a constituents meeting. Six people were killed and 13 people were injured in the morning attack.

On that fateful day, Kelly was not in Arizona but in Houston, Texas with his two teenage daughters, from a previous marriage.

As soon as he was informed of the terrifying news, Kelly rushed to Tucson to be with his wife.

Since the attack, she has undergone multiple surgeries and physical therapy to relearn how to walk and talk.

The Democrat resigned from Congress on January 25, 2012 and Kelly, 48, retired from NASA in June 2011.

In the aftermath of the deadly shootings in Aurora and Newtown, the couple are channeling their energies into activism and have launched a political action committee to push for stricter gun laws.

Though no longer in an elected role, Giffords, 42, and her husband still frequent Capitol Hill to encourage policymakers to adopt tighter regulations for gun owners.

Activists: Gabby Giffords, pictured with her husband Mark Kelly, wore green ribbons in memory of the victims of Sandy Hook as they listened to President Obama's State of the Union address on Tuesday

Together: Mark Kelly supports his wife as she speaks on Jan. 30 at a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing on Capitol Hill to discuss legislation to curb gun violence

Kelly spoke honestly to Vogue about their new effort, PAC Americans for Responsible Solutions.

'We didn’t want to be doing this,' he said.

'There are lots of things we’d rather have done. But sometimes you don’t get a choice. Gabby is "OK, this happened to me. I want it to count for something."'

With his military career behind him, Kelly said that his main mission is to care for his wife.

Interviewer John Powers describes how Giffords 'shares an almost mystical communion with her husband', who can tell what she's thinking before she speaks and who steadies her as she walks, a constant support system who never leaves her side.

The profile highlights the deep bond the couple share, describing 'how easily they work as a unit.'

'Disaster has taken their marriage to a new level of connection and intimacy.'

The couple, who have no children together, have said they haven't given up hope of ever having a family.

Before Loughner's attack they had been trying to have a baby and Gabby had been undergoing fertility treatments, they revealed in their 2011 memoir Gabby: A Story of Courage, Love and Resilience.

In their book, the couple write how two of their frozen embryos are stored at the Walter Reed Medical Center and they most likely would rely on a surrogate, should they pursue parenting.

In love: Gabrielle Giffords married her husband Mark Kelly in 2007

The couple also shared in their book about the raw struggle of walking through the recovery process.

Mark wrote about the low moments of his wife's emotional response as she tried to regain her speech and mobility.

He remembered the moment he saw Gabby realize how drastically her life had changed.

She 'figured out she was trapped. Trapped inside herself. Her eyes were as wide open as I'd ever seen them and the look on her face was one of absolute fear.'

'I could tell what she was thinking: that this was what her life would be like from now on, that she'd never be able to communicate the even the simplest word.'

A close friend of the couple also spoke to Vogue about Giffords' recovery.

'You can see the wheels moving in the brain. She’s understanding everything,' Joni Jones told the magazine.

'We still talk about the same girly things we did before the shooting. She likes clothes and jewelry. She dresses the same way she collects art,' she said, adding that Giffords is still committed to being involved in policy especially after her own experience.

'She’s definitely frustrated. She thinks about what might have been, I’m sure. She’s the type of person who wants to be part of the community and part of the world. But she’s such a positive person that I know she’s tried to transition her focus to what she can do,' Jones added.

With her husband, she has put on a brave face and stayed in the spotlight with the launch of their new anti-violence effort.

Giffords and Kelly were both in attendance on Tuesday night for President Obama's State of the Union address. They both wore green ribbons in memory of the 20 children and six adults killed in the shooting on Dec. 14 in Newtown, Conn.

She was named in a list of gun crime victims by President Obama, who he said deserved the introduction of tighter controls.

The Sandy Hook massacre was also mentioned as was majorette Hadiya Pendleton, who was shot dead three weeks after performing at the President’s inauguration.

President Obama said: ‘Hadiya’s parents Nate and Cleo are in the chamber tonight, along with more than two dozen Americans whose lives have been torn apart by gun violence.

‘They deserve a vote. Gabby Giffords deserves a vote. The families of Newtown deserve a vote.’

This week, the couple's PAC released its first TV ad urging Congress to support tight gun laws.

In it Giffords narrates over images of recent gun massacres: 'We have a problem, where we shop, where we pray, where our children go to school.

'But there are solutions we can agree on, even gun owners like us. Take it from me, Congress must act. Let’s get this done.’
